<DOC><DOCNO> AP880720-0212 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2127EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Burma-Riots     07-20 0186</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Burma-Riots,0192</SECOND><HEAD>New Riots in Southern City, Mobs Destroy Shops</HEAD><DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mobs destroyed shops and other buildingslate Wednesday in new violence in a southern city after weekendriots killed one person and injured six others, official stateradio reported.   The radio gave no casualities, arrests, or other details on thelatest rioting in Prome, about 180 miles north of Rangoon.   The weekend rioting broke out after a teashop owner and customerquarreled. The unrest died down Monday after Buddhist monksappealed for calm.   On Tuesday, state radio reported that 41 people arrested duringMarch 18 riots and packed into a prison van died during a two-hourride to jail. It said the victims were cremated March 19 and thatthe government had delayed release of the news to avoid possiblespread of unrest.   The victims died from tear-gas exposure and the long periodspent in the overcrowded prison van, the radio said.   Home Minister U Min Goung took responsibility for the deaths andresigned, according to the announcement.   The 41 victims were among 71 people arrested during studentriots in Rangoon.</TEXT></DOC>